That sounds about right to me.

But this is clearly going to be one of those Great Divides
in NASCAR fandom.  Folks have got their interpretation of
what DID happen and what SHOULD have happened, and probably
can't be argued out of their view.  It's a blik (perception
of a whole, a Gestalt, an intuitive perception, a combination
of data, insight, understanding, taste, and judgment).

I respect people who have a different blik from mine.

I imagine (without any proof whatsoever--sorry!) that the
guys who have the power to make the call discuss "what-if"
scenarios all season long and all during the off-season
so that when accidents do happen, they have a common view
of what the "right call" is in that situation.

What we need--and don't have and probably can't get--is
a replay of the last eight seconds of the race in tenths
of seconds and with the scoring loops marked on the track.
Then the game begins with estimating the earliest possible
point at which the officials COULD have thrown the flag
and a determination of who was where on the timing loops
at that point.  NASCAR can probably diagram that with
the information they have at their disposal.  I doubt
they'll make it available to us any time soon.  :o)

As the seconds (or tenths of seconds) tick by on this
imaginary replay, we know that Harvick is in front for
some of it and Martin in front for other parts of it.

If MM hadn't wobbled, he might have edged KH at the
line (or so it says in my imaginary replay--YMMV).

KH and his fans could then complain that the yellow
should have flown while KH was ahead on the scoring
loops because that was the "right" time to throw
the caution flag.

For me, it's all part of the fun.  I was entertained
and I'll come back for more.

FWIW, I like Terry Blount's assessment:

http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/columns/story?seriesId=2&amp;columnist=blou...

